y a marsh or fen. Fenn Place in Worth in Sussex had owners called <i>atte Fenne</i>, who in the time of King Henry VI (1421–1471) apparently changed their name to <i>Fenner</i>. See   Fenn  .","English: variant of <b>Fainer</b>, from Middle English <i>feiner</i>, <i>fener</i> ‘haymonger, one who sells hay’ (Old French <i>fenier</i>), or perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>feiner</i> ‘inventor; hypocrite’.","South German and Swiss German: occupational name for an ensign or standard bearer, from Middle High German <i>vener</i>, an agent derivative of Middle High German <i>vane</i> ‘flag’. See also   Fenrich  ."]},{"name":"Fenning","meanings":["English: topographic name from Middle English <i>fen(ne)</i> ‘fen, marsh’ (Old English <i>fenn</i>) + <i>-ing</i>, for someone who lived by a fen or marsh. Compare   Fenn  ."]},{"name":"Finner","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt.","German: topographic name from an agent derivative of Old High German <i>fenni</i>, Middle Low German and Old Frisian <i>fenne</i> ‘bog’ (see   Fenn  ).","German: ethnic name for a Finn (see   Finn   4)."]}]},{"name":"Alicia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Modern Latinate form of   Alice .  It was borne by the British ballerina  Alicia Markova  (born  Lilian Alicia Marks ,  1910–2004 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Alisha","meanings":["Modern Latinate form of   Alice .  It was borne by the British ballerina  Alicia Markova  (born  Lilian Alicia Marks ,  1910–2004 )."]},{"name":"Alisia","meanings":["A form of Alice"]},{"name":"Alyssa","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alissa ."]},{"name":"Alissa","meanings":["Contracted form of   Alicia ."]},{"name":"Alesha","meanings":["Respelling of   Alicia ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":3,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across E